---
// src/pages/faq.astro
import Page from '../layouts/Page.astro';
import BuyButton from '../components/BuyButton.astro';

const breadcrumbs = [{ name: 'FAQ', href: '/faq/' }];

const faqs = [
  {
    q: 'Do I need any botanical knowledge to use these guides?',
    a: `Not at all. The ACE method was designed for anyone who can look at a tree.
        You learn to read bark — does it peel in long ribbons? grip in hard interlocking plates?
        shed cleanly to smooth white or cream? — and then confirm with the fruit capsules,
        which are present year-round. No Latin, no prior training, no special equipment needed.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'Does the guide cover my suburb?',
    a: `The Melbourne edition covers the greater Melbourne region — from the Dandenong Ranges
        in the east to the Otway foothills in the west, including Melbourne's parks,
        bushland reserves, and peri-urban areas. Each species entry notes the local parks
        and reserves where you're most likely to find it.

        The Brisbane edition covers greater Brisbane's bushland reserves, with a map
        and quick-reference list to help you find particular species.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'Does it include a species key?',
    a: `Yes. A visual key at the front sorts species by bark type — the most reliable
        field characteristic because it's present and consistent year-round. Once you've
        placed a tree in a bark category (stringybark, box, ironbark, or gum), you're
        already looking at a small handful of candidates. The fruit narrows it to one.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'Do I need to wait for the tree to flower?',
    a: `No — and that's the whole point. Traditional eucalypt identification often relies
        on flowers, which appear briefly and inconsistently. The ACE method uses bark
        texture and fruit shape, which are present every day of the year. You can make
        a confident identification in any season, on any day you happen to be in the bush.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'Does it include indigenous knowledge?',
    a: `Yes. Each species entry acknowledges the Aboriginal knowledge connected to that
        species and includes names in local language — Wurundjeri Woi-wurrung and
        Bunurong/Boon Wurrung for Melbourne, and local Jagera and Turrbal language names
        for Brisbane. The guides recognise that these trees have been known, named, and
        used by Aboriginal people for tens of thousands of years.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'I\'ve never been able to identify a tree. Will this actually work for me?',
    a: `This is exactly who the guide is written for. The method is step-by-step:
        look at the bark type first — that gives you a category. Then look at the fruit —
        that gives you a species. Most beginners make their first confident identification
        on their first outing. The photography is precise enough that if your fruit matches
        the photo, you've got it.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'Will I actually learn to identify eucalypts, or will I just be looking things up each time?',
    a: `Both, and that's intentional. The guide teaches a repeatable method — not a list of
        facts to memorise, but a way of seeing trees. After a few outings you'll start
        recognising bark types by instinct, and familiar species by sight. The guide stays
        useful even as your knowledge grows, because it's always faster to confirm with
        a photo than to second-guess yourself.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'Do I need to know botanical language?',
    a: `No. The guides use plain English throughout. Where botanical terms are helpful —
        like "operculum" for the cap that pops off a bud, or "pedicel" for the stalk —
        they're explained in context, and the photography makes the meaning immediately
        clear. You won't need a glossary to use the guide in the field.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'What does each species entry include?',
    a: `For each species you get: high-resolution photography of bark, leaves, buds,
        and fruit — all the characteristics you need to make a positive identification.
        Identification notes covering the distinguishing features. Habitat information
        and notes on where to find the species in local parks and reserves.
        Aboriginal names and knowledge. And for introduced species, notes on where
        they come from and why they're here.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'Will I learn about the local ecology — not just the names?',
    a: `Yes. Each entry covers habitat — what kind of soil, slope, or rainfall the species
        prefers, and what other plants it grows with. The guides also cover evolutionary
        context (why so many eucalypt species? how did they diversify?), habitat values
        for fauna, and the broader ecological role these trees play. It's not just
        an identification tool — it's an introduction to eucalypt ecology.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'What\'s the difference between the Melbourne and Brisbane editions?',
    a: `They cover different regions and different species — 36 for Melbourne (32 indigenous,
        4 introduced) and 37 for Brisbane (36 local, 1 naturalised). The Melbourne edition
        was co-authored by Vicky Shukuroglou and Rod Fensham; the Brisbane edition is
        by Rod Fensham alone. Both use the same ACE identification method and the same
        format. If you spend time in both cities, you'll want both.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'Is it actually pocket-sized?',
    a: `Yes. 48 pages, softcover, designed to go in a jacket pocket or daypack. It won't
        weigh you down on a walk. The photography is printed at a size that's genuinely
        useful for field comparison — big enough to see the detail, small enough to carry.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'Can I use it with children or in an educational setting?',
    a: `Absolutely. The visual method and clear photography make the guides accessible
        from about age 10 upward, and the bark-first approach turns identification into
        a game younger kids can engage with. Teachers have used both editions in
        environmental education programs — the indigenous knowledge sections are
        particularly valued in this context.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'Is it just for botanists and serious naturalists?',
    a: `Far from it. It's written for anyone curious about the trees around them —
        bushwalkers, gardeners choosing indigenous species for their yard, people
        who walk in the same park every weekend and want to know what they're looking at.
        Botanists will find it rigorous and useful. Absolute beginners will find it
        welcoming. That's a hard balance to strike, and it's what makes these guides
        genuinely first-class.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'How do I buy a copy?',
    a: `Both editions are available directly through this website via secure Stripe checkout —
        $30 AUD per copy plus $6 postage anywhere in Australia. No account needed.
        You can also order either edition through any Australian bookshop using the ISBN,
        or find them at selected retailers including the Australian Koala Foundation.
        Bulk and wholesale orders: email aceguidetoeucalypts@gmail.com.`,
  },
];

const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: faqs.map(({ q, a }) => ({
    '@type': 'Question',
    name: q,
    acceptedAnswer: {
      '@type': 'Answer',
      text: a.replace(/\s+/g, ' ').trim(),
    },
  })),
};
---

<Page
  title="FAQ — ACE Guide to Eucalypts"
  description="Frequently asked questions about the ACE Guide to Eucalypts — Melbourne and Brisbane editions. Do you need botanical knowledge? Does it cover your suburb? Does it include indigenous knowledge?"
  schemaJson={faqSchema}
  breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}
>
  <h1>Frequently asked questions</h1>

  <p class="faq-intro">
    Everything you want to know before picking up the guide — and a few things
    you didn't know you wanted to know.
  </p>

  <div class="faq-list">
    {faqs.map(({ q, a }) => (
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary class="faq-question">{q}</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          {a.trim().split(/\n\s*\n/).map(para => (
            <p set:html={para.trim().replace(/\n/g, ' ')} />
          ))}
        </div>
      </details>
    ))}
  </div>

  <div class="faq-cta">
    <p>Ready to take one into the bush?</p>
    <div class="faq-buttons">
      <BuyButton text="Buy Melbourne — $36 AUD" href="https://buy.stripe.com/00w3cn2Wi7Yq7uf3pXgjC01" external={true} />
      <BuyButton text="Buy Brisbane — $36 AUD" href="https://buy.stripe.com/4gM6ozcwSguW5m78KhgjC02" external={true} />
    </div>
    <p class="faq-secure">Secure checkout via Stripe. No account needed.</p>
  </div>
</Page>

<style>
  .faq-intro {
    font-size: 1.125rem;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-lg);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  .faq-list {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0;
  }

  .faq-item {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-olive);
  }

  .faq-item:last-of-type {
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-olive);
  }

  .faq-question {
    display: block;
    padding: var(--space-md) 0;
    font-family: var(--font-heading);
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-text);
    cursor: pointer;
    list-style: none;
    position: relative;
    padding-right: 2rem;
    line-height: 1.4;
  }

  .faq-question::-webkit-details-marker {
    display: none;
  }

  .faq-question::after {
    content: '+';
    position: absolute;
    right: 0;
    top: var(--space-md);
    font-size: 1.4rem;
    font-weight: 300;
    color: var(--color-olive);
    line-height: 1;
    transition: transform 150ms ease;
  }

  details[open] .faq-question::after {
    content: '−';
  }

  .faq-question:hover {
    color: var(--color-cta);
  }

  .faq-answer {
    padding-bottom: var(--space-md);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  .faq-answer p + p {
    margin-top: var(--space-sm);
  }

  /* CTA */
  .faq-cta {
    margin-top: var(--space-xl);
    padding-top: var(--space-lg);
    text-align: center;
  }

  .faq-cta > p:first-child {
    font-family: var(--font-heading);
    font-size: 1.3rem;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-md);
  }

  .faq-buttons {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: var(--space-sm);
    justify-content: center;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-sm);
  }

  .faq-secure {
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
  }
</style>
